<DOC><DOCNO> AP890911-0001 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 2324EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Refugees-Glance 1stLd-Writethru a0658 09-11 0278</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Refugees-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0658,0280</SECOND><HEAD>Glance at Developments in Mass Exodus of East Germans to West Germany</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with Die Welt reporting 10,000East Germans crossed into the West. Picks up graf 4 pvs, `East Germany's...'</HEAD><DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here is a glance of the keydevelopments in the mass exodus of East Germans to West Germanythrough Hungary:   _ Hungary announces Sunday it will allow thousands of vacationingEast Germans to leave for West Germany, and the exodus throughAustria begins shortly thereafter. Hungarian border guards atHegyeshalom, about 120 miles northwest of Budapest, are instructedto let all East Germans through with only cursory checks.   _ East German refugees, many crammed in private cars, beginarriving in Passau, West Germany, early Monday after an all-nightdrive. More than 2,000 arrive in West Germany by midday. The WestGerman newspaper Die Welt reports in its Tuesday edition that about10,000 East Germans crossed into the West on Monday.   _ East Germany's state news media Monday denounces Hungary'saction as ``illegal'' and charges that its Warsaw Pact ally ``underthe guise of humanitarism is engaging in organized smuggling ofhumans.''   _ West Germany's ZDF television network reports East Germanleader Erich Honecker is in failing health after his gall-bladdersurgery three weeks ago. ZDF also says ``critics in the Politburoreportedly are charging that Honecker misjudged the meaning andscope of the wave of refugees.''   _ West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, in a speech Monday inBremen, calls on his countrymen to welcome the East German refugeesand to have faith in the future of a reunified Germany.</TEXT></DOC>